            {
                "s2_paper_id": "ae99038eaa54cb960e730059aaf9fe583ba515d9",
                "title": "Radio numbers for generalized prism graphs",
                "year": 2010,
                "venue": "Discussiones Mathematicae Graph Theory",
                "citation_count": 37,
                "reference_count": 14,
                "abstract": "A radio labeling is an assignment c : V (G) ! N such that every distinct pair of vertices u,v satisfies the inequality d(u,v )+ |c(u) c(v) |diam(G) + 1. The span of a radio labeling is the maximum value of c. The radio number of G, rn(G), is the minimum span over all radio labelings of G. Generalized prism graphs, denoted Zn,s, s 1, n s, have vertex set {(i,j)|i =1 ,2 and j =1 ,...,n} and edge set",
                "authors": [
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "2066122179",
                        "name": "Paul Martinez"
                    },
